	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Making the GSP more secure</h1>

			
			<h4>
												03 April 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>Two law academics at Cambridge and Berne Universities have proposed that developed countries should bind their Generalised System of Preferences (GSP) schemes at the WTO. When countries ‘bind’ their tariffs in this way they cannot normally impose higher tariffs without breaking WTO rules (unless a temporary increase is justified by a specific safeguard clause). At present, WTO members only bind their most favoured nation (MFN) tariffs – the highest tariff that they are allowed to impose on imports from any other member. Although breaches of preferential tariffs under a negotiated agreement (such as the EPAs) are not outlawed in the WTO, they can be referred by an aggrieved party to the agreement’s dispute settlement mechanisms. There is no such defence, however, if a developed country unilaterally alters (or abolishes) its GSP tariffs. This means that the GSP is an inherently unstable preference system (though major changes by providers have been rare). It has been argued that this instability weakens the impact of the preferences by discouraging investment: potential investors, it is argued, are unwilling to make long-term commitments for fear that access terms for the resulting exports will change before the investment payback period is complete.</p><p>The two authors make clear that their proposal does not prejudge the desirability of trade preferences. They recognise that critics have claimed that they hurt non-beneficiaries (whose exports are hit) and even beneficiaries (by discouraging diversification). They argue, however, that ‘tariff preferences will remain part of the landscape of international trade regulation for the foreseeable future.’ Their ‘proposal proceeds from this basis and seeks to extract the maximum possible gain from this system, by embedding preferences in a legal framework ...’ They show that both the GATT/WTO texts and case law allow TWO members to bind multiple tariff levels under Article II.I of GATT – i.e. that they could bind both an MFN and a GSP (and an FTA) rate if they wished to do so. They also argue that countries would not lose control over the details of their GSPs in this way. The authors consider a number of qualifications that countries may wish to include in a GSP offer, and argue that these would not be prejudiced by binding. Similarly, they query ‘whether autonomous rules of origin could continue to be applied to bound tariff preferences’, and conclude that they could. In other words, each GSP-granting state can fashion whatever origin rules it wishes to apply to the scheme.</p><p>Just how much flexibility countries would retain over their GSP scheme is illustrated by the EU decision to extend for a further year the transitional period for Cape Verde’s graduation out of the EBA scheme. This measure was agreed since the economic crisis had ‘hampered Cape Verde’s economic diversification efforts’. It was also held that the-three year transitional period ‘has not allowed the time necessary for Cape Verde to overcome the over-reliance on one key export sector and thus alleviate potential adverse effects of the removal from the EBA scheme.’</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
<i>Journal of International Economic Law</i>, ‘Binding tariff preferences for developing countries under Article II GATT’, by L. Bartels and C. Häberli, on the possible binding of GSP preferences at the WTO, Vol. 13, No. 4, 2010<br />

<a href="http://jiel.oxfordjournals.org/content/13/4/969.full.pdf+html" target="_self">http://jiel.oxfordjournals.org/content/13/4/969.full.pdf+html</a><br />
European Commission, ‘Commission Regulation (EU) No. 1126/2010 of 3 December 2010 … as regards an extension of the transitional period for withdrawing the Republic of Cape Verde from the list of beneficiary countries of the special arrangement for least developed countries’, <i>Official Journal of the European Union</i>, 4 December 2010<br />
<a href="http://www.acp-eu-trade.org/library/files/EC_EN_41210_EC_Cape%20Verde%20EBA.pdf" target="_self">http://www.acp-eu-trade.org/library/files/EC_EN_41210_EC_Cape%20Verde%20...</a>&nbsp;</p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Over half of the ACP states have seen in the EU’s GSP an acceptable alternative to EPAs. Most of these states, being LDCs, are eligible for the most preferential ‘Everything But Arms’ (EBA) tranche of the GSP, but some of the others could become eligible for GSP+ if they ratify and implement all of the international social and environmental conventions that are a required under its rules. Only the EBA arrangement provides an equivalent level of access for agricultural exports as the EPAs, but both schemes offer better agricultural preferences than the standard GSP. With the latest change to the EU’s rules of origin for the GSP (see <i>Agritrade</i>&nbsp;article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Thesaurus-labels/Agriculture/Commodities/General" target="_blank">EU agrees new rules of origin’</a>, January 2011), the rules for LDCs (though not for non-LDCS) are very similar to those under the EPAs.</p><p>One major difference remains, however, between EPAs and the GSP: the EU can alter the latter unilaterally at any time, but it cannot legally change the former without the agreement of the ACP (unless it abrogates the EPAs entirely). Adoption of the proposal to bind GSP tariff rates would remove this difference. However this is only a proposal by private individuals – only if developed countries act upon this proposal will the status quo change.</p>
		</div>
		
